utterances.speaker: MIKE EMANUEL, CORRESPONDENT
utterances.utterance: This is a Fox news alert. I'm Mike Emanuel in Washington. The United States Geological Survey is giving an update on the California earthquake. Let's listen in.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: In over 40 -- between magnitude three and magnitude four, this is actually what's been expected. And we also have forecast for the probabilities of aftershocks over the next weeks. So there's a 9 percent chance within the next week that we would have an earthquake of greater than magnitude 6.4, which is the main shock. There's also a 20 percent chance that we're going to have greater than magnitude five within that one week period. It's very likely with a magnitude 6.4 that you get aftershocks of those magnitude five. Currently, we have geologist headed out to the field, they should be there later this afternoon to look at -- there's been some reports of ground cracks, there's possibility of actual faulting. And so we actually have the geologist and the reports from the field, we can't confirm that. There have also been reports of damage, several fires in the Ridgecrest area, so that certainly is consistent with what we expected as well. We had -- there were some questions about the shake alert system, I will confirm that the shake alert system, that's the early warning system, it did perform as designed. There were no glitches. There -- in the city of L.A., there's an app to issue warnings. That warning did not go out and the reason why is because the estimated intensity of shaking for Los Angeles was intensity three, the app does not kick in until the expected intensity is above for. So as designed, the app performed as it would -- or as it should. The intensity is within the L.A. area was not strong enough to cause any damage.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: I'm sorry. I just wanted to check, you said at 20 percent chance of greater than a magnitude five (INAUDIBLE) Lucy said earlier 80 percent chance?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: Twenty percent is for magnitude six.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: Yeah. I apologize if I misspoke.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: So, we get you to run through --

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: Yeah. Let me just pull that up here just to make sure we have that correct. Yeah, Lucy, actually -- if you have the numbers, you want to do that?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: Yeah. I think it's important to say we're not predicting a particular earthquake, and that seems to be one of the rumors that got going. We are rather saying here is a rate of earthquakes with those lower magnitudes being much more common than the higher magnitudes, but we can estimate the rate of the larger ones from the smaller ones. And the chance of at least another four is close to 100 percent. The chance of at least a five is about 80 percent. The chance of a six is about 20 percent. And a chance it will be above the magnitude of the main shock, i.e. 6.4., is about 9 percent. All of that is a statement about the same rate, you just choose which one you want -- which magnitude level you want to talk about.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: And even if -- if we did see a magnitude above 6.4, that would still be considered an aftershock?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: Once -- if it's above magnitude 6.4 we would change the name and we would call the first one a foreshock, all right? But, all of those words, foreshock, main shock, aftershock mean they are part of the same sequence with the main shock being by definition the largest one. So, it would say we're part of the same sequence. And that idea that being bigger really matters, that's sort of a centric -- it's a person's idea rather than a physical idea.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: And all those numbers, just to also clarify, all of those probability numbers are for one week period starting from today.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: However, the most likely time is today?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: If we get to tomorrow, those numbers are all quite a bit lower. Those numbers will be down by more than half if we get to tomorrow.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: The science community has discussed the -- what happens after you get an alert. There has been some concern expressed that just getting the alert does not safeguard people. Could you bring up what the key issues are that people need to bear in mind as they are concerned about getting that alert? But are we getting another one?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: What action they should be prepared to take?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: All right. Asking what people should be doing with alerts and where it's all right to do it. Let's remind ourselves this is not a physical science question. Unfortunately, we often have physical scientist trying to give the answer. When there have been social science experiments on what people do, it's not a clean answer. Giving them more alerts convinces people that the system works and generates trust in it. Lots of false alarm generates distrust. Part of the concern and current early system without complete funding, how many false alarms would we be issuing. So that's a factor that goes into the decision. The other problem, of course, is that -- actually, there's a lot of use to the alerts beyond damage. Nobody in Los Angeles County was damaged. Nowhere close. We didn't get anywhere close to it. We've just all felt it. That does not stop people from being scared from feeling it. And one of the questions is what's the psychological benefit of giving a few seconds warning and knowing that it's coming, and that's a hard thing to measure physically and therefore is a hard one to include in those practical decisions of how you do it. And that -- you know, it becomes a decision -- it becomes a committee decision what's the -- you know, balancing off all of these different things, what's the best way to go?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: And what are those? One that you said was a little - -

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: We hypothesized a relationship with little lake, which would be the northwest trending one, but that's something we don't have a number.

And it appears -- what probably happened here, this --

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: Let me point. You talk in the cameras.

utterances.utterance: So let's say were talking about the faults -- there's one that goes northwest and that one goes northeast. And the motion that we expect on that fault is such that it would release the stress -- or confine stress on that fault to the northwest. So, Lucy can show with her hands -- yes?

utterances.utterance: So this one like this, and that whole material --

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: Right, pull the material away at the top, and that release that secondary fault, which -- you know, in essence, participated in the earthquake, but also showing a lot of activity with the aftershock. Again, until we get the geologist in the field, I can't confirm that, but that's the working hypothesis at this point.

utterances.utterance: It get back to that geologic time frame question. We have a national --

utterances.utterance: We can't have Juan win this. Juan won it last time, so we can't have win two in a row. Next up, we finally have the six ears of corn, half a dozen for some, six --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: -- for those of you watching at home. I will shuck the corn if I get this right. I'm in excellent shucker.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Greg, careful. Everybody hold it up.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Dana wins. But Juan wins overall.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: $6.00. A buck a piece of corn.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: There we go everybody. That's how you shuck an ear of corn.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: All right. My mom made me do it back at home in August every single day. A look back at one of our favorite moments of the year, our hit song, shut up about politics. More when THE FIVE returns.

utterances.speaker: EMANUEL
utterances.utterance: I'm Mike Emanuel in Washington. Our top story on this 4th of July, a magnitude 6.4 earthquake struck Southern California and Nevada this morning. It was centered near the town of Ridgecrest about 150 miles northeast of Los Angeles. It occurred at 10:33 AM local time. A California institute technology seismologist says the quake is the strongest to hit Southern California in 20 years. She says it was preceded by a magnitude 4.3 quake about half-hour earlier. There were no immediate reports of major injuries or damage, at least one house fire was reported in Ridgecrest. Dozens of aftershocks are being reported. And another strong quake is said to be possible.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: There is about a 1 in 20 chance that this location will be having an even bigger earthquake within the next few days that we have not yet seen the biggest earthquake of the sequence.

utterances.speaker: EMANUEL
utterances.utterance: Local emergency agencies took to social media to ask people to only call 911 for emergencies consisting of injuries or other dangerous conditions. President Trump tweeted he'd been fully briefed on the situation and that all seemed very much under control. We will have more on the earthquake during an extended two hour addition of Special Report starting at 6 PM Eastern. The National Mall right now is filling up in preparation for President Trump salute to America. We'll have complete coverage, now back to “The Five.”

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Well, I'll never get tired of that song, Dr. Perino.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Thank you. Me neither. It's good for your health.

utterances.utterance: Yes. Take that Morning Joe. And since then, it continues to rack up thousands of downloads each week, all proceeds going to fold of honor which provides scholarships for children and spouses of our fallen and disabled service members. utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You know, Dana, I think we proved once and for all how easy it is to write a number one song. Look, I don't think any rock band or any country band could come and do THE FIVE. No way, that would be a disaster. But we just walked into their world and we scored a number one song. Take that the Cyrus' and the Taylor Swift's.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: And we even own our master.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I don't know if we really do, but --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I am -- it was a dream come true for me. I loved our trip to Nashville. We have our fans in Nashville. I thought it was great, the whole song. Your writing is hilarious, as always good. John Rich did that in one take.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: And that's how you get the number one song.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Jesse, did you learn anything from this experience? I doubt it, but I'm asking.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I dislike how much you have taken credit for the success of the song. And I want to see what you write originally and then what he came up with because I feel like you think you actually co-wrote it when he wrote 99 percent --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: No, I think -- I would say he wrote 70 percent --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes. Actually, in all honesty, I sang it to him. And I --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I serenaded him, and then we talked on the phone, back and forth, before we -- before I allowed him to continue writing.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: And you spent a long time at his house the night we were down there. Until very late at night.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: -- celebrating. And let's not forget the title of the song is mine.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes. I've said that it had to be call and response. Juan, are you disgusted by how petty these people -- Jesse is? He's petty.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Does that surprise you, though, Juan?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But we should celebrate Greg in this moment. Let him have his moment.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I mean, he's the king of late night. I can't have him be king of the Billboard charts, too.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, I think it's great. Again, I think what we did was so fantastic. Dana's idea, Greg -- but, you know, the audience. I keep coming back to the idea that because “The Five” audiences so terrific, they supported us. They responded, right? Most people -- people could have just said, well, OK, these are guys on TV. But, no, people understood what it was about. And I think they understood that also the money goes to a terrific charity.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You know, just speaking of money, Katie, it does go to charity, but shouldn't some of it have gone to me?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You know, I mean, I did help write it. I just think it's a bit - - like, we could have given 80 percent to charity and 20 percent to me, no one would have cared.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Well, that's probably true. You definitely deserve all of the credit and all of the money from here until the end of time.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: It's certainly the best song from the rest of --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: What was your line about charity, it's the best thing you'll ever do, but you won't get any money from it.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: You won't get any money from it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah. I think -- did I say that?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes, you did. I wrote it down.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I remember what he said, the name of his boat, charity.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Well, you know, John Rich is coming back in August --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: -- and he's going to be here on the table, but he's also gonna -- have a little surprise for us.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Even better. I think can we say we're - we're going to - we're going to award the scholarship.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes. We're going to award the scholarship. I thought it was a surprise, Dr. Perino.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I'm not telling you to dance, trying to (ph) make this tease worth it. This student just might go to Med school.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: I don't know. It made me want to learn how to play guitar though.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: By the way, it's so easy.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: No. I haven't. But I've been learning - I've been doing all Cramps songs. I'm learning the first album by The Cramps.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You can hear the stomach growling. All right, anything else before we move on?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Coming up, more of your fan mail questions. Plus, we're squaring off on a brand-new quiz show on “The Five” July Fourth Special.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Welcome back to the party of “The Five.” Happy Fourth of July to everybody. Now, more of your fan mail questions from social media. Instagram question from @yrgirl26, What TV show or movie do you refuse to watch? Katie?

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Oh, it's so creepy and weird. No.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You know, she has a new book coming out, so let's see if it's more entertainment.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: No. I'll watch pretty much anything, even my own show.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, right, lot of people watch your show. No, but seriously, is it was like when you were a kid and your mom said, "Jesse, we don't want you to watch that show."

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: No. I mean I was pretty much allowed to watch anything I wanted to.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: You know if it was inappropriate or past my bedtime, I wasn't allowed to watch it. But--

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But then you'd really watch it.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: --there wasn't anything that I can remember.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: I wasn't allowed to watch MTV.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You weren't allowed to watch MTV?

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Or Little Mermaid because I would be a brat when I would watch it. I would start acting like Ariel.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I did not watch The Bachelor or The Bachelorette.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: And I - I guess I am missing out.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I've - I - I actually tried to watch it a couple of times. I - I hate it.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Now, you got to see Luke Pee (ph). This guy's unbelievable.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I've been watching - I've been very busy with my charity work.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes, my boat. I don't - you know what's - it's - I - I don't want to get - I like Meghan McCain. I like Whoopi Goldberg. But I can't watch The View. Be - and I - and the reason why I said I can't watch The View is because it's always on at the gym, so I'm on the stair climber, and The View is always on.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: So, you're associating it with the stair climber.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: But I mean I don't - I - I - I like listening to Whoopi and Meg - Meghan. But there's just a few people there who just irritate the heck out of me, just, and it's not like - it's not even a political thing.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: But it's just like I just - I just don't need it at 11 in the morning.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes. I would disagree. I think Joy and Whoopi and the whole crew are really talented but for - journalists.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: No, I don't. No, I don't.

utterances.utterance: I think it was a Kumquat.

utterances.utterance: --there's some - there's some fruits and vegetables that aren't meant to be eaten.

utterances.utterance: I know that you're supposed to try something, scare yourself once every day like do something new, I'm trying to think of something I did that was new, and that's not good.

utterances.utterance: --you said that would be the last time.

utterances.utterance: OK. Good, all right, I'll take it. I have to - I did take up tennis, but that's been a couple of years, so no - I don't know.

utterances.utterance: You didn't kill that drifter in the early 90s.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes. Well yes but that's not new.

utterances.utterance: And remember, we showed you of all my acrobatics.

utterances.utterance: Right. In fact, the other day at the gym, I did something I hadn't done, which was rings, you know, where you flip yourself over?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: --I mean if you practice. Yes, I can do it. But the thing is that--

utterances.utterance: We need video of Juan in the rings.

utterances.utterance: I feel like there's something else that happened.

utterances.utterance: You went to England. And you went to the horse race.

utterances.utterance: The Royal Ascot. That's - that was the - the new thing.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: But that wasn't scary. That wasn't like a - an adventurous.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I think - I think maybe you - you know, you thought you were wrong but you were mistaken.

utterances.utterance: She's really slipping by the predecessor (ph).

utterances.utterance: I know. When was the last time you were snooping around and found something you wish you hadn't?

utterances.utterance: I - I don't have - I - I don't have one for myself. But I know of one. It wasn't snooping. But somebody found something that was on a computer that they weren't supposed to have access to, but there was a flaw in the system or something, and they saw, and yes, I - so I know about something that happened.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You're not going to give us a clue?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: It was here - it was here at - at work.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Wait a minute. This is obviously--

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: No. I need to - it's - it's - it's not about anybody here, yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Ooh! So is it - is it about Shep?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Wait a minute! I thought Lou.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Lou? Everybody, you don't mess with Lou.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I don't snoop. I respect privacy. But I did snoop around on Christmas Eve and find some presents. And I made a discovery, this was a long time ago, but kids are watching, so I'm not going to disclose what I discovered.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Next. All right, Katie, you're up. What - what - you snooping around?

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: I think - no, no snooping. But definitely stumbled upon things I didn't want to see. So, I was at Union Station recently at 5 in the morning--

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: --and there was a guy there with no pants on.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You know, kill me to just--

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: So, I wasn't voluntarily snooping. But--

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: - sometimes you just stumble upon things that you can't unsee.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That is - you know, you want to do a little prank in New York City? Any place where you live next to people, slip a sheet of paper under their door that says "Can you please close your curtains?"

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: And that will screw everybody's brain.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: That's - that's Rear Window right there.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes, yes, yes, because people do things, and they don't - they forget that they're in a city when they're doing things, and we see it, and it's I saw--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Remember I told you what I saw--

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes, yes, yes, yes, yes, yes, got it, got it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: --I can't snoop on my wife because every one of her texts are in Russian. So, I'd say everything she - all of her conversation, I can't figure out who she's talking to.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Wait a minute! Don't they have--

utterances.utterance: Don't they have apps for that?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I've looked into them but yes.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: But he found something he didn't want to see by looking into this.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: By the way - by the way, once, on Fourth of July, I went home to visit my parents, long gone, and we took the kids, and at like 2 or 3 o'clock in the morning, we couldn't find the kids, so I went out snooping. Where - where did the kids go? They were with their grandfather, and I can't tell you what they were watching, but they were eating ice cream, watermelon--

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: OK. So, this is a question that comes. Which can you better tolerate, being hot or being cold? Jesse Watters?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I don't like being hot because you could always - if you're cold, get warmer.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: I can't stand being cold. I would rather be blazing hot.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Well given the fact that I'm hot naturally, I'm used to being hot, so I'd say, I don't like being cold.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But you know what? Hot is associated with sunshine that makes me happy.

utterances.utterance: OK. It's trivia time on this Independence Day. Happy Fourth. Find out who will be crowned THE FIVE's Quiz Show Champion? Tom Shillue's here when we return.

utterances.utterance: All right, well it is Fourth of July, and we are ready for a trivia showdown. Tom Shillue is back to test our knowledge on patriotic fun facts--

utterances.utterance: Watters and - Jesse and Juan - Jesse and Juan got that one right.

utterances.utterance: Yes, he was like the worst President.

utterances.utterance: Question number two. Who was the main author of the Declaration of Independence? Would that be A, Benjamin Franklin, B, John Adams, or C, Thomas Jefferson? A, B, or C, getting those cards up, looks like everyone got that one right. It was Thomas Jefferson.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: --The Family Feud is in our future.

utterances.utterance: Are you guys keeping score? I believe Juan is in the lead.

utterances.utterance: Which NASA spacecraft landed safely on the surface of Mars on July 4th, 1997? That was my heyday, the late 90s. A--

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: --B, Galileo, or C, Pathfinder. Discovery, Galileo, or Pathfinder. All the cards are up, and the answer is C, Pathfinder.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Oh, thank goodness, Space Camp paid off.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: There you go. There you go.

utterances.utterance: Space Camp? We are learning too much about you.

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: We have - guys, we have a three-way tie?

utterances.utterance: I'm not sure at - this time.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No, no, it could be Coney Island.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I - I believe this is in America if I'm not--

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: --B, 200 million, or C, 50 million. Take your time--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: --if they're beef hot dogs or pork. They don't specify in the question whether it's in the United States or the type.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Well some people can eat a 100 hot dogs a person--

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Though all hot dogs are great (ph).

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: Could be the beef, could be the pork--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: How about Armour Hot Dogs? Kids love Armour Hot Dogs.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: What - what kind of kids love Armour Hot Dogs, Tom?

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: A, B, or C, it is A. Juan is the winner.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: I wrote it too. I just wrote it out.

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: I'm sorry. You - I didn't - I was looking for an A. Juan--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Tom, how does the song go? Kid--

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: Greg, I think one of our advertising--

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Hey, I know it hurts - it hurts you--

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: I can do the actual letter.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Juan's more patriotic, and I am - I can't take it.

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: So, Juan, you - you take the - you did--

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: Did you write down the 150 million too, Dana?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: No, I wrote down C. I - I - I thought that America was more abstemious than it is.

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: It's always amazing what we've done.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: People are still eating little hot dogs.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: All right, Tom, thank you very much.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Thanks to you. And one more fan mail question is up next.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Welcome back to “The Five.” We have one more question on our Fourth of July Special. It is this question from Helen R. from Facebook. What is one thing you want to do before the summer is over? One thing you want to do before the summer is over, Katie?

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Having a camping at the summer, time to get out and do that.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: --and like in on the beach camping or mountain camping?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Out West or on the East Coast.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Well I prefer out West, but I don't think that's going to happen.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: So, unfortunately - I mean East Coast has lots of camping. Don't - don't worry. But--

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: All right, camping - camping is what you want to do.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Juan, what would you want to do before the summer is over?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I haven't thought of it. But, you know, it's one of those things where the summer goes so quickly, there's so much I want to do, I can't think of any one thing, Dana.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: --you want to go to baseball game or basketball? I don't know, basketball that's not even--

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well I plan to see the fireworks tonight, so that'll be great. But I'm just trying to think--

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: All right, you can, we might--

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: How about a concert? I want to go to a music concert.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Because I'm told it's good for my health and I haven't gone to a concert--

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: You should go to Jazz in the Park at the Smithsonian.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: There you go. There you go.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Jesse Watters, what do you want to do before the end of the summer?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I want to go surfing. I've never surfed. I could probably be a pretty good surfer because I was a great skateboarder as a youth, and I'm an excellent swimmer, so I think if I combine those two things, I could really do that.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: And you're a beach guy, not a pool guy.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I'm a beach guy, not a pool guy, right.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: All right, you're going to put Rookie on the surfboard?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: No. Let's take it one step at a time.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I would like to participate in some kind of mystical mysterious ritual in the woods.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: In which people wear like white linen and they walk out--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: --and in kind of - in a precision, almost kind of Wicker Mannish. I--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: --you know, I - I would like to do something mystical and strange.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Is Marianne Williamson leading a crew towards--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Once she becomes President, you won't be laughing then--

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: I will be jealous of your camping excursion.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Well since I'll be VP, you know.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I'm going to - I made a - a New Year's resolution that I would make it to my family's ranch in Newcastle, Wyoming in 2019. It's happening.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I'm going to make it there. So it's one thing I want to do before the summer.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: You are - everybody is welcome to come. That's--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Oh, that's her way of saying she doesn't want to be alone with you.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: See, do you mind if I tag alone? Oh, sure--

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Let me just tell you my - my cousin Preston, he's got a horse ready for you--

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But that's what I was going to ask. So, when you go to the ranch, you do horseback riding?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I think that yes, I'll get - I'll - I'll hop on a horse, yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I'll - I will ride a little bit. I think they said we have one - time for one more question because, you know, this is the Fourth of July Special.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Good night - Katie - OK what does that say?

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: It says what product do you wish a company would make a "smart" product of?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: What product do you wish that company would make a smart product of?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: It's not the product for me, as you know, it's the packaging. For example, Imodium is in fact, Imodium, when you buy it, it's an emergency, but you can't open it, because, look, you can't - and also Pepto, the little Pepto tabs that come in the wrapper, you can't - you can't open them.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: That is a - that is a problem. Anybody else want a company to make something smart?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I do. I want smarter packaging like for your Amazon purchases when they come. I don't want to have to put the cardboard away because it's very complicated. You got to break it all down and everything. And I'm worried about the environment, really.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: You know, and now are you--

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You know what I like? I like smart refrigerators because you can go and get crushed ice right away.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: I want things to be less--

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I know. But I don't have one. I want one.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: You want - oh, Katie wants less smart.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: She wants to go back to that time when she learned how to hunt because you're going to--

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Yes. You can drive a stick shift without all the fancy--

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No, smart cars, you're going to drive it off (ph).

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: --we're celebrating two big things, Jesse's birthday--

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: --and “The Five's” eighth anniversary. You've been with us for eight years. We're going to celebrate that. We'll be broadcasting live from outside on the Fox News Plaza. Be sure to join us. And that's it for us on the Special Edition of “The Five.” We hope you all have a wonderful Fourth of July. We'll see you back here tomorrow. "Special Report" is up next.
